  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions involves several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed historically\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the 1970s\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislative attempt to combat money laundering\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large cash transactions\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created comprehensive recommendations for national legal frameworks\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US RICO Act provisions\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- International conventions addressing money laundering\n- Increased cooperation between nations\n- Standardization of legal approaches\n- Expanded criminal penalties\n\n6. Modern Trends:\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Increased international collaboration\n- More sophisticated detection techniques\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
